{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "The four-year model of residential campus life is becoming obsolete.", "abstract": "Op-Ed article by Prof Mitchell L Stevens opposes common college admissions model under which young, high-school graduates are both assumed to be vast majority of undergraduate body and favored over older students; holds that placing responsibility for college decision and shaping of campus life with young students can lead to number of ill effects, from failure to graduate to financial loss to psychological stress; calls for rethinking of four-year college model and better integration of younger and older people on campus.", "section_name": "Opinion", "print_page": "35", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"lastname": "STEVENS", "rank": 1, "firstname": "Mitchell", "role": "reported", "organization": "", "middlename": "L."}], "original": "By MITCHELL L. STEVENS", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/12/opinion/college-for-grown-ups.html", "lead_paragraph": "The four-year model of residential campus life is becoming obsolete.", "headline": {"main": "College for Grown-Ups", "print_headline": "College for Grown-Ups", "content_kicker": "Op-Ed Contributor", "kicker": "Op-Ed Contributor"}, "_id": "548a4ee038f0d8017fa650d2", "word_count": "762", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2014/12/12/opinion/12stevens/12stevens-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2014/12/12/opinion/12stevens/12stevens-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 438, "url": "images/2014/12/12/opinion/12stevens/12stevens-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2014/12/12/opinion/12stevens/12stevens-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "438"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2014/12/12/opinion/12stevens/12stevens-thumbStandard.jpg", "legacy": {"thumbnail": "images/2014/12